{{One source|date=September 2012}}
A '''daybill''' is one variety of [[Australia]]n [[film poster]] issued to [[movie theater|cinemas]] at the time of a film's release. A daybill measures approximately {{convert|13|by|30|in|mm}}, however during [[World War II]] some daybills measured {{convert|10|by|30|in|mm}} because it allowed an additional daybill to fit onto the sheet of paper.<ref name=moviemem>{{cite web|title=Australian daybills 1941-1960|url=http://www.moviemem.com/pages/page.php?page=30|work=Australian Movie Posters|publisher=Movie Memorabilia|accessdate=7 September 2012}}</ref> 

Daybills were folded twice and sold to cinemas for 5 to 10 cents.<ref name=moviemem/>

Until the 1970s, most daybills were printed as [[lithograph]]s. In the 1960s some posters began copying [[United States|American]] [[printing]] techniques to achieve a 'gloss' finish that suited the [[photograph]]ic images that were becoming prevalent in poster design. Today, daybills are printed on thick glossy paper and are much more durable.

Daybills are sought-after by [[Collecting|collectors]] for their rarity and unique [[Visual arts|artwork]]. Some of the more famous daybills include:

* [[Halloween (1978 film)|Halloween]] ([[John Carpenter]], 1978). Features a unique image of villain [[Michael Myers (Halloween)|Michael Myers]]. Australia was the only country to depict Myers on the poster.
* [[The Empire Strikes Back]] ([[George Lucas]], 1980). Features artwork developed in [[Japan]], but considered superior among many collectors.

