{{Bantu-lang-stub}}

The '''Lange-Taylor Prize''' (or '''Dorothea Lange‚ÄìPaul Taylor Prize''') is a prize awarded annually by the Center for Documentary Studies at [[Duke University]], Durham, NC, to encourage collaboration between documentary writers and [[Documentary photography|photographers]].<ref>{{cite magazine | year = 2015 | title = Better Together | first = Olivier | last = Laurent | periodical = [[Huck (magazine)|Huck]] | issue = 52 | pages = 12‚Äì17 | publisher = TCOLondon Publishing}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = Dorothea Lange‚ÄìPaul Taylor Prize overview | publisher = Center for Documentary Studies, Duke University | url = https://documentarystudies.duke.edu/awards/lange-taylor}}</ref> The prize, that has variously been $10,000 and $20,000 (USD), is named after photographer [[Dorothea Lange]] and her husband, writer [[Paul Schuster Taylor]]. It has been awarded since 1990.
==Recipients== *2003: Misty Keasler and [[Charles D'Ambrosio]].<ref>{{cite web|url = http://documentarystudies.duke.edu/awards/dorothea-lange-paul-taylor-prize/prizewinners/2003-prizewinners | accessdate = 8 December 2014 | publisher = Duke University | title = 2003 Winners: Misty Keasler and Charles D'Ambrosio}}</ref> *2004: Katherine Dunn and Jim Lommasson.<ref>{{cite web|url = https://documentarystudies.duke.edu/awards/lange-taylor/prizewinners/2004 | accessdate = 1 June 2018 | publisher = Duke University | title = 2004 Winners: Katherine Dunn and Jim Lommasson}}</ref> *2005: [[Kent Haruf]] and Peter Brown.<ref>{{cite web|url = https://documentarystudies.duke.edu/awards/lange-taylor/prizewinners/2005 | accessdate = 1 June 2018 | publisher = Duke University | title = 2005 Winners: Kent Haruf and Peter Brown}}</ref> *2006: [[Donald Weber (photographer)|Donald Weber]] and Larry Frolick.<ref>{{cite web|url = https://documentarystudies.duke.edu/awards/lange-taylor/prizewinners/2006 | accessdate = 1 June 2018 | publisher = Duke University | title = 2006 Winners: Larry Frolick and Donald Weber}}</ref> *2007: Kurt Pitzer and Roger LeMoyne.<ref>{{cite web|url = https://documentarystudies.duke.edu/awards/lange-taylor/prizewinners/2007 | accessdate = 1 June 2018 | publisher = Duke University | title = 2007 Winners: Kurt Pitzer and Roger LeMoyne}}</ref> *2008: Ilan Greenberg and [[Carolyn Drake]] for ''Becoming Chinese: Uighurs in Cultural Transition''.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://documentarystudies.duke.edu/awards/lange-taylor/prizewinners/2008 | accessdate = 1 June 2018 | publisher = Duke University | title = 2008 Winners: Ilan Greenberg and Carolyn Drake}}</ref> *2009: Teru Kuwayama and [[Christian Parenti]].<ref>{{cite web|url = https://documentarystudies.duke.edu/awards/lange-taylor/prizewinners/2009 | accessdate = 1 June 2018 | publisher = Duke University | title = 2009 Winners: Teru Kuwayama and Christian Parenti}}</ref> *2010: Tiana Markova-Gold and Sarah Dohrmann.<ref>{{cite web|url = https://documentarystudies.duke.edu/awards/lange-taylor/prizewinners/2010 | accessdate = 1 June 2018 | publisher = Duke University | title = 2010 Winners: Tiana Markova-Gold and Sarah Dohrmann}}</ref> *2013: Jen Kinney.<ref>{{cite web|url = https://documentarystudies.duke.edu/awards/lange-taylor/prizewinners/2013 | accessdate = 1 June 2018 | publisher = Duke University | title = 2013 Winner: Jen Kinney}}</ref> *2014: [[Jon Lowenstein]].<ref>{{cite web|url = https://documentarystudies.duke.edu/awards/lange-taylor/prizewinners/2014 | accessdate = 1 June 2018 | publisher = Duke University | title = 2014 Winner: Jon Lowenstein}}</ref> *2015: Michel Huneault awarded the $10,000 prize for ''Post M√©gantic.''<ref>{{cite web | url = http://time.com/4043624/canada-lac-megantic-train-disaster/ | date = 21 September 2015 | access-date = 3 November 2015 | first = Lucia | last = De Stefani | publisher = [[Time (magazine)|Time]] | title = Michel Huneault Wins Dorothea Lange‚ÄìPaul Taylor Photo Prize}}</ref> Honorable Mention awarded to Alice Leora Briggs and Juli√°n Cardona for ''Abecedario de Ju√°rez.'' Special Recognition awarded to Serge J-F. Levy for ''The Fire in the Freezer.''<ref>{{cite web | url = http://pdnpulse.pdnonline.com/2015/09/10k-lange-taylor-prize-goes-to-michel-huneault-for-project-about-oil-train-disaster.html | date = 21 September 2015 | access-date = 3 November 2015 | first = Conor | last = Risch | publisher = [[Photo District News]] | title = $10K Lange‚ÄìTaylor Prize Goes to Michel Huneault for Project About Oil Train Disaster}}</ref> The other finalists were JT Blatty; [[Kitra Cahana]]; Sarah Christianson and Sierra Crane Murdoch; Megan E. Doherty; Jess Dugan and Vanessa Fabbre, Justin Maxon; Brittany M. Powell; Rylan Steele and Nora Wendl; Byron Wolfe, Mark Klett, and Rebecca Solnit.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://documentarystudies.duke.edu/awards/lange-taylor/prizewinners/2015 | access-date = 1 June 2018 | publisher = [[Duke University]] | title = 2015 Prizewinner: Michel Huneault}}</ref> *2016: Steven M. Cozart awarded the $10,000 prize for ''The Pass/Fail Series.'' Honorable Mentions Awarded to Carlotta Cardana and Danielle SeeWalker for ''The Red Road Project'' and to Phyllis Dooney and Jardine Libaire for ''Gravity Is Stronger Here.''<ref>"[https://documentarystudies.duke.edu/awards/lange-taylor/prizewinners/2016 2016 Lange-Taylor Prize:Steven M. Cozart, "The Pass/Fail Series"]", Duke University. Accessed 28 November 2017.</ref> *2017: Katherine Yungmee Kim for ''Severence''. An Honorable Mention was awarded to photographer and visual artist [[Marco Panzetti]] for ''The Idea of Europe''. Other finalists for the 2017 Lange-Taylor Prize were Cassi Alexandra, Constanze Han, Anthony Karen and Whitney Kimball, [[Julia Spicher Kasdorf]] and Steven Rubin, Marie-Luise Klotz, [[Alia Malek]] and [[Peter van Agtmael]], Lucas Olivet, Isadora Romero and Misha Vallejo, Sara Sallam, Suchitra Vijayan, Carletta Carrington Wilson, and Gesche W√ºrfel.<ref>{{cite web|url = https://documentarystudies.duke.edu/projects/2017-lange-taylor-prize-katherine-yungmee-kim-severance | accessdate = 1 June 2018 | publisher = Duke University | title = 2017 Prizewinner: Katherine Yungmee Kim}}</ref>
