{{merge to|Heteronormativity|date=August 2018|discuss=Talk:Heteronormativity#Merge proposal: Merge Queer erasure here}}
'''Queer erasure''' is a [[heteronormative]] cultural practice where [[queer]] people are erased from cultural narratives.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theodysseyonline.com/queer-erasure-heteronormativity|title=Queer Erasure And Heteronormativity|last=|first=|date=2016-11-28|work=The Odyssey Online|access-date=2018-08-26|language=en-us}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Scot |first1=Jamie |title=A revisionist history: How archives are used to reverse the erasure of queer people in contemporary history |journal=QED: A Journal in GLBTQ Worldmaking |date=2014 |volume=1 |issue=2 |pages=205-209 |doi=10.14321/qed.1.2.0205 |url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/10.14321/qed.1.2.0205 |accessdate=27 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Mayernick|first=Jason|last2=Hutt|first2=Ethan|date=June 2017|title=US Public Schools and the Politics of Queer Erasure|url=https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/full/10.1111/edth.12249|journal=Educational Theory|language=en|volume=67|issue=3|pages=343‚Äì349|doi=10.1111/edth.12249|issn=0013-2004|via=}}</ref> Queer erasure (inclusive of [[lesbian]], [[gay]], [[bisexual]] and [[Asexuality|asexual]] erasure) is used in both scholarly and popular media texts when referring to issues of visibility and exclusion, such as in the case of [[AIDS research]] that does not include lesbian populations.<ref name="Smith">{{cite book |last1=Smith |first1=Anna Marie |editor1-last=Plummer |editor1-first=Ken |title=Modern Homosexualities: Fragments of Lesbian and Gay Experiences |date=1992 |publisher=Routledge |location=London |isbn=9780415064217 |pages=200-213 |url=https://www.taylorfrancis.com/books/e/9781134922437/chapters/10.4324%2F9780203210628-27 |accessdate=31 August 2018 |chapter=Resisting the erasure of lesbian sexuality: A challenge for queer activism}}</ref><ref name="guardian">{{cite news |last1=Salmon |first1=Caspar |title=Casting Jack Whitehall as a gay Disney character is an act of queer erasure {{!}} Caspar Salmon |url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2018/aug/15/jack-whitehall-gay-disney-queer-erasure |work=Guardian |date=15 August 2018 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Shamir's 'Straight Boy' Video Spotlights Queer Erasure |url=https://www.out.com/music/2017/10/11/shamirs-straight-boy-video-spotlights-queer-erasure |language=en |date=11 October 2017}}</ref> Historian Gregory Rosenthal refers to queer erasure in describing the exclusion of LGBTQ histories from public history that can occur in urban contexts via gentrification.<ref name="Rosenthal">{{cite journal |last1=Rosenthal |first1=Gregory |title=Make Roanoke Queer Again |journal=The Public Historian |date=1 February 2017 |volume=39 |issue=1 |pages=35‚Äì60 |doi=10.1525/tph.2017.39.1.35 }}</ref> 

