'''«ÄXam''' (/Kham) ({{IPA-all|{{!}}Õ°xam}}, English pronunciation {{IPAc-en|Àà|k|…ëÀê|m}}), or ''«ÄXam Ka«Ék ºe'', is an [[list of extinct languages|extinct]] [[Khoisan language]] of South Africa, part of the [[Tuu languages|«ÉUi branch of the Tuu languages]]. It is closely related to the [[Endangered language|moribund]] [[N«Ång language]]. Much of the scholarly work on «ÄXam was performed by [[Wilhelm Bleek]], a German [[linguistics|linguist]] of the 19th century, who studied a variety of «ÄXam spoken at Achterveld, and (with [[Lucy Lloyd]]) another spoken at Strandberg and Katkop.<ref>G√ºldemann (2011)</ref>

== Name ==
The pipe at the beginning of the name "«ÄXam" represents a [[dental click]], like the English [[interjection]] ''tsk, tsk!'' used to express pity or shame. The {{angbr|x}} denotes a [[voiceless velar fricative]] click accompaniment.

Compared to other Khoisan languages, there is little variation in rendering the name though it is sometimes seen with the simple orthographic variant ''«ÄKham'', as well as a different grammatical form, ''«ÄKhuai''.

== Phonology ==

=== Consonants ===
Compared to other Tuu languages like [[Taa language|Taa]], «ÄXam has a more restricted inventory of consonants particularly the clicks, where there are only 8 series of click accompaniments, far fewer than East !Xoon Taa's 18.<ref name=":0">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QvpwwRLYai0C|title=The Khoesan Languages|last=Vossen|first=Rainer|date=1 January 2013|publisher=Psychology Press|isbn=9780700712892|page=210|language=en}}</ref> A preliminary consonant inventory of «ÄXam, including egressive stops, fricatives, and affricates as well as ingressive clicks, is listed below.
